Key Concepts I Learned


Microsoft Entra Security Defaults and Conditional Access are important security features that help organisations protect their identities and resources. Security Defaults provide baseline protection, while Conditional Access enables administrators to apply more granular security controls, such as enforcing multifactor authentication (MFA) based on specific conditions.


Authentication and authorisation serve different purposes. Authentication verifies the identity of a user or device, while authorisation determines what resources and actions an authenticated user is permitted to access.


The authentication methods discussed during the session included Single-Factor Authentication (SFA), Multifactor Authentication (MFA), and Passwordless Authentication. Passwordless authentication methods, such as Windows Hello for Business, provide stronger security by eliminating reliance on traditional passwords.


Privileged Identity Management (PIM) enables organisations to implement Just-in-Time (JIT) access for privileged accounts, reducing security risks by granting elevated access only when required for administrative tasks.


Two PIM assignment types were covered:

Eligible Assignment – Users must activate the role before they can use it. Activation may require MFA, justification, or approval depending on the configured settings.
Active Assignment – Users can immediately use the assigned role without completing an activation process.



When deploying a Conditional Access policy, it is considered best practice to test the policy with a limited set of users or groups and utilise Report-Only Mode before organisation-wide deployment. This approach helps prevent accidental lockouts and service disruptions.



Lab / Hands-On Activities
Activities Performed
During the practical session, I replicated the demonstrations provided by the instructor by configuring a Conditional Access policy and implementing Privileged Identity Management.
Conditional Access Policy Configuration

Signed in to the Microsoft Entra Admin Centre.
Navigated to Conditional Access and selected Policies.
Created a new policy and assigned it a descriptive name.
Assigned the policy to a designated test user.
Configured the policy under Access Controls to require Multifactor Authentication.
Saved and enabled the policy.

Privileged Identity Management Configuration

Navigated to ID Governance and selected Privileged Identity Management.
Selected Microsoft Entra Roles.
Located the Group Administrator role.
Opened the role settings and selected Edit.
Configured activation settings to require both justification and approval before role activation.
Reviewed the activation duration and notification settings.
Assigned a test user as Eligible for the Group Administrator role.


Results Obtained
Conditional Access Policy

Upon signing in with the test user account, the user was prompted to register and configure Multifactor Authentication before gaining access.
This confirmed that the Conditional Access policy was functioning as intended and had been successfully applied.

Privileged Identity Management

The eligible user initiated activation of the Group Administrator role.
An approval request was generated and reviewed from an administrator account.
Following approval, the role became active for the configured duration, enabling the user to perform the administrative functions associated with the role.


